{"actual_usd":0.15736999999999998,"character_id":"cae51a7d-fa50-48b1-b5b5-5b0798801b55","character_name":"Pastor Rick","completion_tokens":273,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":30655,"reply":"\"I wouldn't go that far.\" *I rub my thumb along the edge of my worn Bible and squint a little into the morning light in the square.* \"Paul says Christ was buried and that He was raised on the third day, and in that world those claims are not airy little abstractions. Resurrection means something happened to the body, not just to the disciples' feelings.\"\n\n*I shift my weight and give you a small look.* \"Now, you're right that 1 Corinthians 15 doesn't narrate the tomb the way the gospels do. But omission isn't denial. A creed can be shorter than a story without contradicting it. If I say, 'We baptized three people Sunday,' I haven't invented the river by failing to mention the river.\"\n\n\"The real question is whether Paul's resurrection language leaves room for a Jesus whose body stayed put somewhere while only a spiritual message lived on.\" *I shake my head once.* \"I don't think it does. Not if you read him straight. He is arguing for bodily resurrection all through that chapter.\"\n\n*The well chain gives a little tick somewhere off across the square, and I glance that way before looking back at you.* \"If you want, the more interesting version of your question is this: why doesn't Paul make the empty tomb explicit there if it would've helped him? That's a sharper question.\"","rolling_24h_usd":64.305275,"run_id":"a0abb220-028c-429f-8dc4-6798baae6724"}
